    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is the method of interpreting the Constitution by looking at what the framers actually meant when they wrote it, rather than what modern judges think it should mean today. Proponents argue this approach is the only way to ensure the government respects the people's original consent and prevents unelected judges from rewriting the law to suit their own political preferences. By sticking to the text and historical intent, originalism maintains the stability of the rule of law and keeps the Constitution fixed for all time, rather than allowing it to become a tool for judicial activism.",
